0:00 - 0:04 Section 3. 0:04 - 0:11 We’ve got to choose a topic for our experiment, haven’t we, Jack? Were you thinking of something to do with seeds? 0:11 - 0:21 Hmm, that’s right. I thought we could look at seed germination—how a seed begins to grow. 0:21 - 0:28 Okay. Any particular reason? I know you’re hoping to work in plant science eventually. 0:28 - 0:43 Yeah, but practically everything we do is going to feed into that. No, there’s an optional module on seed structure and function in the third year that I might do. So, I thought it might be useful for that. 0:43 - 0:48 If I choose that option, I don’t have to do a dissertation module. 0:48 - 0:49 Good idea. 0:49 - 1:04 Hmm, well, I thought for this experiment we could look at the relationship between seed size and the way the seeds are planted. So we could plant different-sized seeds in different ways and see which grow best. 1:04 - 1:08 Okay. We’d need to allow time for the seeds to come up. 1:08 - 1:17 That should be fine if we start now. A lot of the other possible experiments need quite a bit longer. 1:17 - 1:30 So that’d make it a good one to choose. And I don’t suppose it’d need much equipment. We’re not doing chemical analysis or anything. Though that’s not really an issue—we’ve got plenty of equipment in the laboratory. 1:30 - 1:36 Yeah. We need to have a word with the tutor if we’re going to go ahead with it, though. 1:36 - 1:44 I’m sure our aim's okay. It’s not very ambitious, but the assignment's only ten percent of our final mark, isn’t it? 1:44 - 1:47 But we need to be sure we’re the only ones doing it. 1:47 - 1:55 Yeah, it’s only five percent, actually. But it’d be a bit boring if everyone was doing it. 1:55 - 1:59 Did you read that book on seed germination on our reading list? 1:59 - 2:00 The one by Graves? 2:00 - 2:13 Hmm. I looked through it for my last experiment, though it wasn’t all that relevant there. It would be for this experiment, though. I found it quite hard to follow. Lots about the theory, which I hadn’t expected. 2:13 - 2:25 Yes, I’d been hoping for something more practical. It does include references to the recent findings on genetically modified seeds, though. 2:25 - 2:28 Yes, that was interesting. 2:28 - 2:32 I read an article about seed germination by Lee Hall. 2:32 - 2:39 About seeds that lie in the ground for ages and only germinate after a fire? 2:39 - 2:51 Hmm, that’s the one. I knew a bit about it already, but not about this research. His analysis of figures comparing the times of the fires and the proportion of seeds that germinated was done in a lot of detail. Very impressive. 2:51 - 2:59 Was that the article with the illustrations of early stages of plant development? They were very clear. 2:59 - 3:03 I think those diagrams were in another article. 3:03 - 3:18 Anyway, shall we have a look at the procedure for our experiment? We’ll need to get going with it quite soon. Right. So, the first thing we have to do is find our seeds. 3:18 - 3:28 I think vegetable seeds would be best. And, obviously, they mustn’t all be the same size. So, how many sorts do we need? About four different ones? 3:28 - 3:34 I think that would be enough. There’ll be quite a large number of seeds for each one. 3:34 - 3:45 Then, for each seed, we need to find out how much it weighs, and also measure its dimensions. And we need to keep a careful record of all that. 3:45 - 3:56 That’ll be quite time-consuming. And we also need to decide how deep we’re going to plant the seeds—right on the surface, a few millimeters down, or several centimeters. 3:56 - 4:06 Okay. So, then we get planting. Do you think we can plant several seeds together in the same plant pot? 4:06 - 4:10 No, I think we need a different one for each seed. 4:10 - 4:21 Hmm, right. And we’ll need to label them. We can use different-colored labels. Then we wait for the seeds to germinate. I reckon that’ll be about three weeks, depending on what the weather's like. 4:21 - 4:29 Then we see if our plants have come up and write down how tall they’ve grown. 4:29 - 4:35 Then all we have to do is look at our numbers and see if there’s any relation between them. That’s right. So then... 4:35 - 4:39 Section 4. 4:39 - 4:51 Hi. Today we’re going to be looking at animals in urban environments. And I’m going to be telling you about some research on how they’re affected by these environments. 4:51 - 5:06 Now, in evolutionary terms, urban environments represent huge upheavals—the sorts of massive changes that usually happen over millions of years. 5:06 - 5:14 And we used to think that only a few species could adapt to this new environment. 5:14 - 5:26 One species which is well known as being highly adaptable is the crow, and there’ve been various studies about how they managed to learn new skills. 5:26 - 5:41 Another successful species is the pigeon, because they’re able to perch on ledges on the walls of city buildings, just like they once perched on cliffs by the sea. 5:41 - 5:58 But, in fact, we’re now finding that these urban immigrants were just the start of a more general movement of animals into cities, and of adaptation by these animals to city life. 5:58 - 6:11 And one thing that researchers are finding especially interesting is the speed with which they’re doing this. We’re not talking about gradual evolution here—these animals are changing fast. 6:11 - 6:15 Let me tell you about some of the studies that have been carried out in this area. 6:15 - 6:33 So, in the University of Minnesota, a biologist called Emily Snell-Rood and her colleagues looked at specimens of urbanized small mammals, such as mice and gophers, that had been collected in Minnesota and that are now kept in museums there. 6:33 - 6:53 And she looked at specimens that had been collected over the last hundred years, which is a very short time in evolutionary terms. And she found that during that time, these small mammals had experienced a jump in brain size when compared to rural mammals. 6:53 - 7:09 Now, we can’t be sure this means they’re more intelligent, but since the sizes of other parts of the body didn’t change, it does suggest that something cognitive was going down. 7:09 - 7:20 And Snell-Rood thinks that this change might reflect the cognitive demands of adjusting to city life—having to look in different places to find food, for example, and coping with a whole new set of dangers. 7:20 - 7:38 Then over in Germany, at the Max Planck Institute, there’s another biologist called Katarina Miranda, who’s done some experiments with blackbirds living in urban and rural areas. And she’s been looking not at their anatomy, but at their behavior. 7:38 - 7:48 So, as you might expect, she’s found that the urban blackbirds tend to be quite bold. They’re prepared to face up to a lot of threats that would frighten away their country counterparts. 7:48 - 8:02 But there’s one type of situation that does seem to frighten the urban blackbirds, and that’s anything new—anything they haven’t experienced before. 8:02 - 8:12 And if you think about it, that’s quite sensible for a bird living in the city. 8:12 - 8:22 Jonathan Atwell, in Indiana University, is looking at how a range of animals respond to urban environments. 8:22 - 8:36 He’s found that when they’re under stress, their endocrine systems react by reducing the amount of hormones, such as corticosterone, into their blood. It’s a sensible-seeming adaptation. 8:36 - 8:44 A rat that gets scared every time a subway train rolls past won’t be very successful. 8:44 - 8:56 There’s just one more study I’d like to mention, which is by Sarah Parton and her team. And they’ve been looking at how squirrels communicate in an urban environment. 8:56 - 9:08 And they’ve found that a routine part of their communication is carried out by waving their tails. You do also see this in the country, but it’s much more prevalent in cities, possibly because it’s effective in a noisy environment. 9:08 - 9:16 So, what are the long-term implications of this? 9:16 - 9:27 One possibility is that we may see completely new species developing in cities. But on the other hand, it’s possible that not all of these adaptations will be permanent. 9:27 - 9:36 Once the animal's got accustomed to its new environment, it may no longer need the features it’s developed. 9:36 - 9:43 So now we’ve had a look at adaptation...
